## 13. Key design principles (apply everywhere)

1. **One screen, one task.** No screen should collect information AND explain a concept at the same time.

2. **User is reviewer, not author.** Wherever possible, the AI drafts and the user confirms. Never present a blank form when the AI can pre-fill it.

3. **Source attribution on all AI extractions.** Every extracted field must show where it came from (from inbox / AI-inferred / user-provided). No invisible AI decisions.

4. **Restricted words are hard constraints.** Not suggestions. Not soft preferences. The AI never uses them. Enforce in post-processing.

5. **Brand kit is the source of truth.** Every generation re-injects the full kit. Never let iterations drift away from the kit by carrying only the previous output forward.

6. **? tooltips on every input field.** One line answering "why does this help me?" — not "what is this field." Sakshi's principle: curse of knowledge — users don't know what we're asking without explanation.

7. **Enterprise language throughout.** No "No credit card required", no "Get started free", no personal Gmail auth. Every CTA, label, and error message should read as if it was written for a procurement-aware professional.

8. **Never trap the user.** Every screen with a forward action has a back option. The confidence test always shows "Back to kit" regardless of reaction state.

